This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Science sub-category of Network and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) as it deals with bandwidth aggregation for multi-interface enabled devices. It may also belong to the sub-category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) as it discusses the security implications of bandwidth aggregation. Additionally, it could be categorized under Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) as it proposes a system that dynamically schedules connections or packets to different interfaces. It may also fall under the sub-categories of Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Information Theory (cs.IT) as it involves designing a system that estimates the characteristics of applications and dynamically schedules connections to different interfaces to maximize throughput.
